what is your current working directory?
I suspect you are starting python from the onnxruntime source directory? if so, change to any other directory and start python again.
if your current working directory has a subdirectory named onnxruntime, python will try to import that subdirectory as a module , which obviously won't work.

No, if in `onnxruntime` dir, it will can not import onnxruntime since it does not a python package.
I cd to another dir to test.

My question is, the onnxruntime seems installed, the tests can pass, but can not using InferenceSession , and I can not found any wheel under `build`.

How to skip the test  anyway?

add --update --build to your build.sh command
i.e. 
./build.sh \
        --cuda_version=10.1 \
        --cuda_home=/usr/local/cuda-10.1 \
        --cudnn_home=/usr/local/cuda-10.1 \
        --use_tensorrt --tensorrt_home=$HOME/TensorRT \
        --build_wheel --update --build

the default option set internally is --update --build --test 
you can disable tests by explicitly setting the options and leaving off --test

I don't know am I link against  tensorrt right or not since I test onnxruntime-gp-tensorrt compares with force CPU, it faster than CPU but not fast as I expected on tensorrt, much more slower than pytorch GPU compares on maskrcnn.onnx model.

In the present working directory, you can not have a file whose name is the same as the module name.  
In easy words the module you are importing is `onnxruntime` and if there is a file name in your working directory as `onnxruntime.py` then the import will be failed because the compiler is confused about what it should load, file, or a module.  
### What can you do?
either change your working directory where you are executing the code (recommended), or rename `onnxruntime.py` to another name.  
### How did I solve it?
In my case, I created a file with the name of `onnxruntime.py` and in the `onnxruntime.py` I imported `import onnxruntime as nxrun` and it gave the error when I renamed the `onnxruntime.py` to `runonnxmodel.py` it did not give that error.

### Reference:
open this [StackOverflow answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/64509910) for more detail about the error reason.
